IORn03nSTRUCTUREn04nINTERIORnnrn05n06nPLUMBINGnELECTRICALn07nHEATING/COOLING/VENTILATIONnInspectednResidentialnCONDITION KEYnGoodnIn good working order or condition for its age, functionality is better than expected.nGenerally good ornTypical for its agenOkaynIn a condition that shows some deterioration and may require some remediation ornmaintenance. Functionality and condition have declined somewhat, but are still okay.nAveragenCondition in which may no longer function as intended, deterioration to the point thatnremediation is required.nPoornCompletely deteriorated and is no longer functioning as intended. Replacement is likelynrecommended.nIn a condition realistically expected of the age and type, functioning as intended.nGENERAL BUILDING ELEMENTS GLOSSARYnRoofingnBargeboard - Boards on a gable end.nFacia - Linear metal or timber facings that run along the bottom of a roof line.nHips & Valleys - Internal or external elements of a roof creating either a valley or a ridge.nCeiling Cavity - Space between the ceiling and the cladded roof.nCladdingnCavity System - The gap between two surfaces e.g. cladding to frame cavity.nCladding - Material fixed to the exterior of a dwelling.nDirect Fixed - Fixed directly with no cavity.nMonolithic - Smooth rendered plaster finish over a selected substrate.nVermin Strip - Strip used to allow airflow but stop rodents accessing.nSoffits - Overhanging horizontal lining under the overhanging roof.nEaves - Pitched section of roof overhang.nFlooringnJoinerynAppliances &nMechanicalnElectricalnPlumbingnConcrete Slab - Solid concrete foundation on which something is built.nRing Foundation - A narrow concrete perimeter around the outside of a dwelling.nPiles - Vertical structural elements being the base of the foundation.nJoists - Runs on or between bearers to create a frame for the floor.nBearers - Thick horizontal elements running over piles to create load support.nJoinery - Windows, doors, cabinetry.nJam/frame - The frame around a door.n