cialist. All rusted sections should benreplaced. Flashings around the chimney should be sealed and adjusted to prevent water pooling on them.nConcrete capping in the top of the chimney should be replaced as it has cracking through it.nExteriornWater damaged soffit sheets should be replaced once the gutter leaks have been fixed. The weatherboardsnon the garage gable end need replacing. The rest of the weatherboards are generally fine but are in need ofna repaint or stain to prevent them aging. Some minor re-pointing needed to any cracking to the mortar on thenbrick cladding. Check rubber seals on joinery and replace any that have perished or shrunk.nStructurenSeveral wet and elevated moisture readings taken. Please refer to moisture section of this report forncomments.nInteriornSome painting and decorating needed to improve the interior. Some rotting noted to two of the garage doornreveals. These sections are best replaced. The interior doors are in general need of attention and adjustingnto improve them.nPlumbingnMonitor hot water cylinder as it is very dated and may be near the end of its life expectancy. It isnrecommended that an extraction fan be installed to the bathroom. Refer to moisture section of this reportnregarding shower stall leak.nElectricalnNo general concerns found.nHVACnNo general concerns found.nEQC scope commentsnThe EQC scope of works supplied appears to have been partially completed. Works outstanding are that thennorthern patio has not been epoxy repaired and painted and re-pointing to the brick masonry has not beenncarried out.nROOF OVERVIEWnLIMITATION(S) in this sectionnTo comply with health and safety at work regulations, the assessment of the roof and its elements is limited tonwhat can be visually assessed from a 3.8m ladder. Any areas not reasonably accessible or unable to bensighted from a ladder are excluded from this report.nConditionnIn generally poor to average condition.nCHIMNEY(S)nConditionnIn okay condition for its age.nCommentsnD