Winter: Check insulation and weatherstripping; clear snow and ice from walkways.nAs Needed Maintenance:n\u00b7 Address plumbing leaks: Promptly repair any leaks to prevent water damage.n. Electrical faults: Get any potential issues checked by an electrical specialist as theynarise, i.e. flickering lights, buzzing noises, signs of excessive heat build-up, etc.n. Pest control: Deal with infestations as they arise.n. Appliance maintenance: Follow the manufacturer's recommendations for yournappliances.n. Inspect and clean septic tanks: If applicable, maintain septic systems as needed.n. Evaluate and maintain swimming pools: Ensure proper chemical balance andnequipment maintenance.n. Inspect and clean ventilation systems: Ensure proper airflow and air quality.nJnBorernInformationnWhat is Borer?nInspectednResidentialnBorer is a pest capable of causing significant damage to timber in homes and other structuresnthroughout New Zealand. Small (2-4mm) flight holes on the surface of timbers, doors and furniturenare signs that borer is present in your home. Another obvious sign is fine sawdust piles close tonthe holes.nWhat causes Borer infestation?nBorer are drawn to seasoned or moist untreated timber. They are commonly found on thensouth-facing sides of buildings or in floor timbers that are prone to dampness. Borer prefer softnor untreated wood and are often found in untreated native timbers in older homes built before then1960s. Some types of wood, such as macrocarpa, are naturally resistant to insect attack, andnkiln-drying radiata pine improves its resistance to borer. Sawn timber is also more susceptible tonborer attack than timber with a smooth surface.nWhat do you do if you have a Borer infestation?nTimber infested with borer can be treated, but if the damage is severe, the timber may need to benreinforced or replaced. The only long-term solution for borer is a residual surface treatment with anproduct containing insecticide or preservative. It's essential that the treatment lasts longer than thenborer's lifecycle, which can range from 4 to 11 years depending on the species. This treatment cannonly be applied to bare timber, so paint or varnish coatings may need to be removed first.nAirborne treatments like bombs, misting, or fogging will only kill the adult borers and won't stopnthe larvae from continuing to damage the timber. Furniture can be treated by fumigation through ancertified pest control company or by injecting insecticide into the flight holes.nIf your inspector has advised they believe borer may be present in the property, it isnrecommended that you engage a suitably qualified pest control professional tonconfirm this before proceeding with treatmentnAsbestosnInformationnWhat is Asbestos?nInspectednResidentialnAsbestos refers to a group of six naturally occurring minerals composed of thin, needle-like fibresnfound in rock and soil. These fibres are so small that they can only be seen under a microscope.nWhy was Asbestos used?nAsbestos was widely used in construction until the mid-1980s due to its resistance to heat,nelectricity, and corrosion. It is commonly found in materials like sprayed-on fireproofing, sound-nproofing, thermal insulation, decorative coatings, vinyl flooring, cement products, roofing sheets,nand pipe lagging.nWhy is Asbestos dangerous?nWhen asbestos-containing materials (ACMs) are disturbed, they release tiny fibres into the air.nInhaling these fibres poses serious health risks, as they can become lodged in the lungs and leadnto diseases such as asbestosis, lung cancer, and mesothelioma.nWhat should you do if Asbestos is present?nUndisturbed asbestos poses minimal risk, and removal is typically unnecessary. However, if thenmaterial is damaged, it should be addressed promptly. In most cases, asbestos removal must bencarried out by a qualified professional with a WorkSafe licence.nIf your inspector suspects the presence of asbestos in your property, it'snrecommended to engage a suitably qualified professional to confirm this,nespecially if any damage is observed.nLeaky HomesnInformationnWhat is a leaky home?nInspectednResidentialnA leaky home is where moisture gets trapped between the exterior cladding and interior wallnframes due to cracks in the exterior cladding and the absence of a cavity system that is designednto ventilate any moisture that may get in. This can lead to rotting of the frames, mould growth andndamage to the interior of the home. High-risk homes are typically Mediterranean-style homes withnmonolithic cladding, commonly built between the late 1980s and mid-2000s.nHow can I identify a leaky home?nThere are often few visible signs that a building is leaky, but certain features, including itsnconstruction year, can suggest its likelihood of leaking. Major risk factors include insufficientnground clearance, cracks in the cladding or joinery, penetrations or openings in the cladding,nwindow flashings, and enclosed balconies or cantilevered decks.nWhat do you do if you think there are leaks/moisture issues?nLeaky buildings can be expensive to repair. A non-invasive moisture test is the first step to locatingnany potential moisture ingress.nYour inspector will advise if any high readings are taken and recommend that anninvasive test be completed by a suitably qualified professional if required.nLnLead-BasednPaint InformationnWhat is lead-based paint?nInspectednResidentialnAs the name suggests, it is paint containing the heavy metal lead. Lead is added to paint tonaccelerate drying, increase durability, maintain a fresh appearance, and resist moisture, which canncause corrosion.nCan you identify lead-based paint?nUnfortunately it's not possible to identify lead-based paints by appearance, however, there arenkits available to test for the presence of lead. Health New Zealand advises that if the propertynwas built in the 1980s or earlier, it is best to presume that lead-based paint was used.nWhy is lead-based paint dangerous?nIncorrect removal of lead-based paints can result in lead poisoning due to ingestion of the paintndust, which has severe health risks.nWhat can I do if my property has lead-based paint?nIf the paint is in good condition, there is minimal risk. However, deteriorating paint is a healthnhazard and needs immediate attention, especially in the interior of the home. There are manynmethods to removing lead-based paint, such as wet sanding, dry sanding, scraping, andnwaterblasting.nDue to the hazardous nature of airborne lead, it is highly recommended that younconsult a suitably qualified professional to remove any lead-based paint to preventnit spreading past the affected area(s) and remaining on the property.nInspectednResidentialnTERMS OF SERVICEn1. How these Terms Apply You are taken to havenexclusively accepted and are immediatelynbound, jointly and severally (where there isnmore than one purchaser), by these terms ofnservice when any one of the following occurs:na. place an order or booking for Servicesnfrom us directly or via any third-partynbooking system; and/ornb. accept our Services by permitting entry bynus to the nominated Premises to performnServices; and/ornc. issue a purchase order to us followingnreceipt of a Quote/Cost Estimate,nand together these terms apply in conjunctionnwith any specific exclusions or additional termsnspecified in any Quote/Cost Estimate.n2. Our Contract Your acceptance of thenQuote/Cost Estimate and these general termsntogether constitute our agreement with youn(this Contract). This Contract governs thenagreement between INSPECTED RESIDENTIALnLIMITED (COMPANY NUMBER 8466019) (\"we\"n\"us\" and \"our\") and you, the named client innthe Quote/Cost Estimate, in respect of thenServices.n3. \"Business Days\" Any reference to 'BusinessnDays' in these terms means a day on whichnbanks are ordinarily open and excludes anSaturday, a Sunday or a public holiday. Anynother reference to a 'day' shall meanncalendar day.n4. \"Healthy Homes Standards\" are the applicablenstand